# Application Server vs Web Server

## Infrastructure Design

This infrastructure hosts the website **[www.foobar.com](http://www.foobar.com)** using a more scalable and reliable setup.

```text
User Browser
     |
     v
DNS: www.foobar.com
     |
     v
Firewall
     |
     v
HAProxy Load Balancer 1  <---- cluster ---->  HAProxy Load Balancer 2
     |
     v
Web Server
Nginx
     |
     v
Application Server
Application Code Base
     |
     v
Database Server
MySQL
```

## Explanation

A user wants to access **[www.foobar.com](http://www.foobar.com)**. The browser resolves the domain name using DNS, then sends the request to the load balancer.

We add **one extra server** to improve the infrastructure and separate responsibilities. Instead of placing all components on the same machines, each major component now has its own server.

We add another **HAProxy load balancer** and configure it as a cluster with the existing load balancer. This removes the load balancer as a single point of failure. If one load balancer fails, the other one can continue receiving traffic.

We split the components into separate servers:

The **web server** runs **Nginx**. Its job is to receive HTTP/HTTPS requests, serve static files, and forward dynamic requests to the application server.

The **application server** runs the backend application logic. It processes user requests, executes business logic, and communicates with the database when needed.

The **database server** runs **MySQL**. It stores persistent data such as users, posts, sessions, orders, or any information that must be saved.

## Web Server vs Application Server

A **web server** mainly handles client requests and responses. It serves static content like HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and images. It can also act as a reverse proxy and forward requests to the application server.

An **application server** runs the actual backend code. It handles dynamic logic, authentication, validation, calculations, database queries, and API responses.

In simple terms:

```text
Web Server = receives requests and serves/forwards them
Application Server = runs the application logic
Database Server = stores the data
```

## Why This Design Is Better

This design is better because each server has a clear responsibility. It is easier to scale, easier to maintain, and more reliable.

If traffic increases, we can add more web servers or application servers. If the database becomes slow, we can improve the database server separately.

This separation also improves security because each server can have specific firewall rules and access permissions.
